Subject: Navier-Stokes Anti-Blowup Gate Matrix

Description: Math inquiry tool for comparing candidate formal meanings of the source document's surface tension and phase-correction language against known anti-blowup proof requirements.

& [NavierStokesAntiBlowupGateMatrix] is a project-local math inquiry tool
  + [tool_uuid] is bb5bcf11-b454-4cbd-8f34-b07b54b83f44
  + [problem] is Navier-Stokes Existence and Smoothness
  + [created_at] is 2026-06-26
  + [trigger_record] is C:\Project\Pinky\.sop\events\proof_inquiry\2026-06-26_navier_stokes_periphery_proof_shape_001.sop
  + [role] is test whether a candidate stabilizing concept can actually block blowup under a known continuation or regularity criterion
  + [not_role] is proving Navier-Stokes, validating simulations, or treating dissipation as enough by itself

& [MatrixColumnSet] is the comparison surface
  + [candidate_control] is the proposed formal meaning of surface tension, anchor, or phase correction
  + [controlled_quantity] is energy, enstrophy, vorticity norm, strain norm, critical norm, alignment geometry, or other quantity
  + [regularity_criterion_contact] is the known criterion or continuation gate it would satisfy
  + [scaling_status] is subcritical, critical, supercritical, geometric, or unclear
  + [anti_concentration_job] is how it prevents finite-time concentration
  + [known_boundary] is known estimate, criterion, heuristic, special case, or open frontier
  + [symbolic_fit] is how it maps to surface tension, resonance anchor, phase correction, or error diffusion
  + [next_question] is the next bounded research question

& [UseProcedure] is the matrix workflow
  + [step_001_list_candidates] is list possible formal mappings for the symbolic stabilizer
  + [step_002_attach_criterion] is tie each candidate to a known regularity or blowup criterion
  + [step_003_score_scaling] is mark whether the quantity is strong enough for 3D criticality
  + [step_004_find_gap] is identify where the candidate fails to control blowup
  + [step_005_adjust_proposition] is narrow the source-document claim to the candidate with best formal pressure

  = must: separate energy dissipation from global smoothness proof
  = must: distinguish known criteria from quantities actually proven bounded
  = must: preserve scaling status
  = should: prefer candidates that contact critical regularity criteria
  - never: treat physical intuition about smoothing as an a priori estimate

& [CurrentApplication] is the first planned matrix
